'''Thiago Furukawa Lucas''' (born 10 November 1984),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ykp3.seesaa.net|title=榎宮さんちのぶろぐ|publisher=seesaa.net|accessdate=12 January 2016}}</ref> who goes by his [[pen name]] {{nihongo|'''Yuu Kamiya'''|榎宮 祐|Kamiya Yū}}, is a [[Brazilians|Brazilian]]-born [[Japan]]ese novelist and illustrator.<ref name="bbc brazil">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.com/portuguese/noticias/2009/03/090325_mangabrasileiroet.shtml|title=Brasileiro faz sucesso como desenhista de mangá no Japão|trans-title=A Brazilian man is successful as manga designer in Japan|first=Ewerthon|last=Tobace|date=25 March 2009|publisher=BBC Brasil|location=Brazil|language=Portuguese|accessdate=12 January 2016}}</ref> <!-- and moved to Japan at the age of seven. {{citation needed|date=October 2017}} --> He worked on Takaya Kagami's light novel adaptation of ''[[A Dark Rabbit Has Seven Lives]]''.<ref name="ann 20131229"/> In 2013, he then worked on writing and illustrating his own light novel series ''[[No Game No Life]]'' which has been adapted into anime,<ref name="ann 20131229"/> was listed as one of the top-selling light novels in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-01-03/top-selling-light-novels-in-japan-by-series-2014/.82853|title=Top-Selling Light Novels in Japan by Series: 2014|date=3 January 2015|work=Anime News Network|accessdate=12 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-01-03/top-selling-light-novels-in-japan-by-volume-2014/.82854|title=Top-Selling Light Novels in Japan by Volume: 2014|date=3 January 2015|work=Anime News Network|accessdate=12 January 2016}}</ref> and was one of ten light novel series to receive a [[Yomiuri Shimbun]] Sugoi Japan Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-03-12/yomiuri-shimbun-sugoi-japan-awards-winners-announced/.85910|title=Yomiuri Shimbun's 'Sugoi Japan Awards' Winners Announced|date=12 March 2015|work=Anime News Network|accessdate=12 January 2016}}</ref> In 2015, his newer light novel and manga series ''[[Clockwork Planet]]'' was greenlit for an anime adaptation.<ref name="ann 20151225"/> In 2011, he married Mashiro Hiiragi, who would work on the manga adaptation of ''No Game No Life''.

